# Backend Rules

These rules apply to all backend code.

References:

- docs/coding-standards.md
- docs/tech-architecture.md
- docs/api-specification.md
- docs/database-design.md
- docs/enums.md

---

# Technology Stack

Framework

- .NET 9
- ASP.NET Core

Libraries

- MediatR
- FluentValidation
- Entity Framework Core
- Serilog

Database

- PostgreSQL

---

# C# Rules

Use modern C# features.

Prefer:

```csharp
var user = new User();
```

Use file scoped namespaces.

Preferred:

```csharp
namespace Cashback.Application.Features.Users;
```

Avoid nested namespaces.

---

# Async Rules

All I/O operations must be async.

Examples:

- Database
- HTTP Calls
- File Operations

---

Method names must end with Async.

Good:

```csharp
GetUserByIdAsync()
```

Bad:

```csharp
GetUserById()
```

when async.

---

Always pass CancellationToken.

Good:

```csharp
await repository.GetByIdAsync(
    id,
    cancellationToken);
```

---

# Controller Rules

Controllers must be thin.

Controller responsibilities:

- Receive request
- Forward request
- Return response

Nothing else.

---

Good:

```csharp
public async Task<IActionResult> Create(
    CreateOrderCommand command,
    CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    var result = await mediator.Send(
        command,
        cancellationToken);

    return Ok(result);
}
```

---

Forbidden:

- Business Logic
- DbContext Queries
- External API Calls

---

# MediatR Rules

All use cases must use MediatR.

Use:

- IRequest
- IRequestHandler

Commands

Write operations.

Queries

Read operations.

---

One use case = one handler.

---

# Handler Rules

Handlers contain application logic.

Handlers may:

- Call repositories
- Call infrastructure services
- Execute business rules

Handlers must NOT:

- Return entities
- Access HttpContext directly
- Perform UI formatting

---

# Validation Rules

Use FluentValidation.

Create validator for every command.

Examples:

```csharp
CreateWithdrawalValidator
GenerateAffiliateLinkValidator
```

---

Validation must NOT be inside:

- Controller
- Repository
- Entity

---

# DTO Rules

Always use DTOs.

Request DTO

```csharp
CreateWithdrawalRequest
```

Response DTO

```csharp
WithdrawalResponse
```

---

Forbidden:

```csharp
return user;
```

```csharp
return order;
```

Entities must never leave backend boundaries.

---

# Result Pattern

Use Result<T>.

Preferred:

```csharp
Result<UserDto>
```

Avoid:

```csharp
throw Exception();
```

for normal business scenarios.

---

Business failures should return Result.Fail().

Examples:

- Insufficient balance
- Invalid withdrawal amount
- User not found

---

# Exception Rules

Exceptions are for exceptional situations.

Allowed:

- ValidationException
- NotFoundException
- ForbiddenException
- BusinessRuleException

---

Do not catch exceptions unless handling them.

Avoid:

```csharp
try
{
}
catch
{
}
```

inside every handler.

Use global exception middleware.

---

# Entity Rules

Entities represent business concepts.

Examples:

- User
- Order
- AffiliateLink
- WithdrawRequest

---

Protect state.

Prefer:

```csharp
public decimal AvailableBalance
{
    get;
    private set;
}
```

Avoid:

```csharp
public decimal AvailableBalance
{
    get;
    set;
}
```

unless necessary.

---

# Repository Rules

Repositories handle persistence only.

Allowed:

- CRUD
- Querying

Forbidden:

- Business Logic
- HTTP Calls
- OAuth Logic

---

Repository Example

```csharp
IUserRepository
IOrderRepository
```

---

# DbContext Rules

DbContext only inside Persistence.

Do not inject DbContext into:

- Controllers
- Domain
- Infrastructure

Prefer repository abstractions.

---

# EF Core Rules

Use Fluent API.

Preferred:

```csharp
builder.Property(x => x.Email)
       .HasMaxLength(255)
       .IsRequired();
```

Avoid DataAnnotations.

---

Use IEntityTypeConfiguration<T>.

One configuration file per entity.

---

# Query Rules

Read operations must use Queries.

Large read operations should use projection.

Preferred:

```csharp
.Select(x => new OrderDto())
```

Avoid:

```csharp
.ToList()
.Select(...)
```

---

Use AsNoTracking() for read-only queries.

---

# Transaction Rules

Use database transactions when:

- Multiple tables updated
- Balance changes
- Withdrawal processing

Examples:

- Withdrawal Completion
- Cashback Approval

---

# Mapping Rules

Do not manually map large objects repeatedly.

Use mapping abstraction.

Allowed:

- Mapster
- AutoMapper

Preferred:

Mapster

---

# Logging Rules

Use ILogger<T>.

Log:

- Errors
- External API Failures
- Business Critical Events

Examples:

- Withdrawal Completed
- Postback Received
- Cashback Approved

---

Never log:

- Passwords
- JWT Tokens
- API Secrets

---

# External API Rules

All external integrations belong in Infrastructure.

Examples:

- AccesstradeClient
- GoogleOAuthClient

Use typed clients.

Preferred:

```csharp
services.AddHttpClient<
    IAccesstradeClient,
    AccesstradeClient>();
```

---

Do not call HttpClient directly inside handlers.

---

# Configuration Rules

Use Options Pattern.

Example:

```csharp
AccesstradeOptions
JwtOptions
GoogleOptions
```

Avoid:

```csharp
configuration["SomeKey"]
```

throughout codebase.

---

# Enum Rules

Use enums defined in:

docs/enums.md

Do not hardcode values.

Bad:

```csharp
if(status == 2)
```

Good:

```csharp
if(status == OrderStatus.Approved)
```

---

# Security Rules

Validate all input.

Never trust client data.

Always authorize protected endpoints.

Use role-based authorization.

Example:

```csharp
[Authorize(Roles = "Admin")]
```

---

# File Organization Rules

One public class per file.

File name must match class name.

Good:

```text
User.cs
Order.cs
GenerateAffiliateLinkHandler.cs
```

---

# Testing Rules

Business logic must be testable.

Prefer constructor injection.

Avoid static dependencies.

Handlers should be unit-test friendly.

---

# Code Generation Checklist

Before generating backend code:

✓ Correct layer

✓ Correct folder

✓ MediatR used

✓ DTO used

✓ Validation exists

✓ CancellationToken used

✓ Async used

✓ No business logic in controller

✓ No entity exposed

✓ Logging considered

✓ Security considered

If any item fails, refactor before completing generation.
